FFF_NC_Level_Select_Inactivity.content: Let's do this for the birdies!
Select a level to fill those feeders!

FFF_NC_Level_Select_Intro.content: Let's select a level to get started!

FFF_NC_Level_3_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: More birds, more feeders and now a new type of feed.
Let’s make sure we put the right type of feed into the right type of feeder.
They’re color coded to help us remember.

FFF_NC_Level_4_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: We’re going to need that to feed all my hungry friends!

FFF_NC_Level_5_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: Yes yes, squirrels like bird food as much as my bird friends.
We must do all we can to keep those squirrels away!

FFF_NC_Level_6_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: Have a lot of feeders to keep full.

FFF_NC_Level_7_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: This feeder can feed up to 4 birds at a time.
Which is most needed because I have lots of new bird friends to feed!

FFF_NC_Level_8_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: They’re gonna get all the bird food!

FFF_NC_Level_9_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: Who knew I had so many fine feathered friends?!

FFF_NC_Level_10_Feed-Feeder_Intro.content: We make this the best feast ever, Daisy!

FFF_NC_Gameplay_Try_to_fill_full_feeder.content: Huh, can't put any more in there.

FFF_NC_Inactivity_Prompt.content: Well what are you waiting for?

FFF_NC_Inactivity_Prompt_with_full_scoop.content: Please put that feed in the feeder.

FFF_NC_Introductory_Animation.content: And soon it will be harder for birds to find food.
Let's feed our fine feathered friends a fabulous feast!

FFF_NC_Tutorial_VO_1.content: First, we must get seeds for the feeder.
Tap the seed bag to help Nature Cat fill his scoop with seeds.

FFF_NC_Tutorial_VO_2.content: Now tap the feeder to help him fill it.

Daisy_Level_2_While_A_Bird.content: While a bird is feeding at this feeder.

Daisy_Level_2_You_Can_Fill_This_Feeder.content: You can fill this feeder with seeds to feed more of our fine feathered friends.

Daisy_Level_1_Intro_Pop_Up_Feed_Feeders.content: Fill this hanging feeder with seeds to feed one bird at a time.

Daisy_Level_1_Fun_Fact_1.content: The blue jay’s favorite foods include bugs, nuts and seeds.

Daisy_Level_1_Fun_Fact_2.content: Blue jays also like to store food to eat later!

Daisy_Level_1_Fun_Fact_3.content: The blue jay can mimic the sound of a hawk!

Daisy_Level_1_Fun_Fact_4.content: Look for blue jays around oak trees. They love acorns.

Daisy_Level_1_Fun_Fact_5.content: Male and female blue jays work together to build their nests.

Daisy_Level_2_MaleCardinal.content: A new bird has arrived. The Male Cardinal.

Daisy_Level_2_Intro_Pop_Up_Feed_Feeders.content: looks like there are even more of our hungry fine-feathered friends.
Good thing we’ve got another feeder.

Daisy_Level_2_Fun_Fact_1.content: You can tell this is a male cardinal by his bright red feathers.

Daisy_Level_2_Fun_Fact_2.content: Check out the beak of the cardinal! It’s great for cracking open seeds.

Daisy_Level_2_Fun_Fact_3.content: Look for cardinals along the edge of a forest and in backyards and fields.

Daisy_Level_2_Fun_Fact_4.content: Cardinals will look for food on the ground, too.

Daisy_Level_3_FemaleCardinal.content: The Female Cardinal has come to join her mate.

Daisy_Level_3_Intro_Pop_Up_Feed_Feeders.content: Check it out, a new feeder!
You can only fill this flat feeder with nuts & berries,
but this feeder can feed two birds at a time!

Daisy_Level_3_Fun_Fact_1.content: A cardinal likes to eat seeds and fruits.

Daisy_Level_3_Fun_Fact_2.content: Cardinals will eat bugs, too, especially when feeding their young.

Daisy_Level_3_Fun_Fact_3.content: The female cardinal has more brown feathers than red.

Daisy_Level_3_Fun_Fact_4.content: A female cardinal will sing while sitting on her nest.

Daisy_Level_4_Chickadee.content: Oh look, Chickadees! And they seem hungry.

Daisy_Level_4_Intro_Pop_Up_Feed_Feeders.content: Oh yeah! Oh yeah!  Another new feeder! The bottle feeder uses seeds, and can feed two birds at a time!

Daisy_Level_4_Fun_Fact_1.content: Seeds, berries, and bugs help black-capped chickadees get through winter.

Daisy_Level_4_Fun_Fact_2.content: will hide their food to eat later,
and can remember thousands of hiding places!

Daisy_Level_4_Fun_Fact_3.content: Black capped chickadees grow new feathers at the end of every summer
to help keep them warm in the winter.

Daisy_Level_4_Fun_Fact_4.content: Other types of birds know the chickadees warning call when a threat is near.

Daisy_Level_5_RedWingedBlackbird.content: Look! Here comes the Red Winged Blackbird.

Daisy_Level_5_Intro_Pop_Up_Feed_Feeders.content: Uh oh, watch out for Squirrels!
They’ll eat all the food in the feeder if we don’t shoo them away.

Daisy_Level_5_Fun_Fact_1.content: Red-winged blackbirds eat mostly insects in the summer and seeds in the winter.

Daisy_Level_5_Fun_Fact_2.content: You can tell a male red-winged blackbird
by its black feathers and red and yellow band on its wings.

Daisy_Level_5_Fun_Fact_3.content: Check out the red-winged blackbird's thin bill!
It’s great for picking out insects hiding in tight places.

Daisy_Level_5_Fun_Fact_4.content: You’ll often see red-winged blackbirds in marshes and fields.

Daisy_Level_6_YellowBreastedWarbler.content: Hey, it’s a Yellow Rumped Warbler.

Daisy_Level_6_Fun_Fact_1.content: In the summer, bugs are the yellow-rumped warbler’s favorite,
but it will also eat fruits and seeds as the seasons change.

Daisy_Level_6_Fun_Fact_2.content: The yellow-rumped warbler is an expert at finding bugs.
You may even see one pluck a bug out of a spider web!

Daisy_Level_6_Fun_Fact_3.content: The yellow-rumped warbler can catch a bug in the air!

Daisy_Level_6_Fun_Fact_4.content: The yellow-rumped warbler may use moose, horse and deer hair in its nest.

Daisy_Level_7_Intro_Pop_Up_Feed_Feeders.content: Here’s a new flat feeder that holds mealworms.

Daisy_Level_8_MaleHairyWoodpecker.content: Hey look, a Male Hairy Woodpecker!

Daisy_Level_8_Fun_Fact_1.content: The hairy woodpecker’s long bill helps it bore holes in trees to find its next meal.

Daisy_Level_8_Fun_Fact_2.content: The hairy woodpecker is a bug eater!
But it also likes to eat fruit and seeds.

Daisy_Level_8_Fun_Fact_3.content: You can tell a male hairy woodpecker apart from the female by the patch of red he has on his head.

Daisy_Level_9_FemaleHairyWoodpecker.content: And now a Female Woodpecker has come to join the male.

Daisy_Level_9_Fun_Fact_1.content: Look for the hairy woodpecker hopping along tree trunks and branches.

Daisy_Level_9_Fun_Fact_2.content: Listen for the hairy woodpecker’s fast tapping, as it looks for food.

Daisy_Level_10_Intro_Pop_Up_Feed_Feeders.content: Man-oh-man, even more squirrels! Nature Cat, what do we do!?

Daisy_Win_1.content: Sweet job! But look, we’ve got more birds to feed.

Daisy_Win_2.content: Oh yeah oh yeah! But here come more hungry birds.

Daisy_Win_3.content: Way to go! But we’ve got more hungry birds incoming.

Daisy_Birdies_To_Get_To_Next.content: birds to get to the next level.

Daisy_Level_1_More_Birds.content: more birds to earn an acorn and get to the next level.

Daisy_You_Won_An_Acorn.content: Keep feeding birdies to win more acorns!

Daisy_Tap_Squirrels.content: Tap on those pesky squirrels to shoo them away!

FFF_NC_Gameplay_Try_to_fill_full_feeder_.content: Can't put any more in there.

Daisy_Intro_Animation.content: But we’ll have to move quickly to keep the feeders filled.

Daisy_Congrats_All_Level.content: Congratulations! You cleared all the levels. Ba-Bam!

Daisy_Win_3b.content: But we've got more hungry birds on their way!

Daisy_Win_2b.content: But here come more hungry birds.

Daisy_Win_1b.content: But look. We got more birds to feed!

Daisy_Keep_Feeding.content: Keep feeding birdies to win more acorns.
